Newbie ramblings - an introduction

I am a new player (and one without any earlier Nomic experience, apart
from reading the Agora mailing logs kept by Vanyel/Don Blaheta for a
few weeks), and I would like to shortly introduce myself and make a
few remarks about things you were discussing in the last few weeks. 


I. Personal stuff

I am  PhD student in theoretical/computational physics at the Ruhr
University in Bochum, Germany. I waste a lot of time surfing the
Internet (that's also how I came across the idea of Nomics, including
Agora). So I guess if you want to know more about me you could try
a look at my Web-Profile, maybe checking out some of my bookmarks
(they are not meant to be used like that, but feel free...):
<http://www.tp3.ruhr-uni-bochum.de/~klaush/Welcome.html>

But now let's get to business :) The Agora issues I am interested in
most are economics and foreign relations, so here are some ramblings
concerning these points.


II. Economics

In a game economics (most importantly the existence of scarce
resources that are somehow required to play) can exist for two
reasons: as a simulation which is fun in its own right, and as a way
to create some pressure on decisions players have to make. 

I think that in a Nomic the latter aspect should be most important -
simulations are much easier to do in a computerized context (sorry if
my job comes through here :). Now I'd rather not say anything against
those of you who have put a lot of effort into preparing more aspects
of an aconomy within Agora (in some recent protos, like those on
resources, plots, production, etc, but also concerning the Agoraverse
as a "virtual space" where these economics can happen). But somehow I
have a feeling that many efforts in that direction could be seen as an
attempt to create something MUD-like within a Nomic - of course with
the advantage over MUDs that everything can be changed, because there
are no hardware or code based restrictions. But with the huge
disadvantage that every single small transaction has to be done by
hand by real humans. The pragmatic currencies proposal and the
discussions around it show how much repetitive and boring work is
involved even at a rather elementary level. Do we really want to
reinvent the MUD concept and run one by hand?

On the other hand, I think that some pressure on the political
decision making (which certainly is a focus of a Nomic game) could be
produced in much simpler ways using the structures that already
exist. Ignoring the technical problems around "Restore Game Balance"
there is such a huge number of VTs and P-notes around that I would
really like to ask you (this is an honest question, not a rhetorical
one, so I'd appreciate getting some answers!): did you ever feel that
you did not have enough VTs or P-notes to do things you wanted to do?
I don't mean just the general habit of being present instead of
voting on not-so-hot issues - did you ever face a "tough" decision
whether to use a VT or P-note or not? Or is one of the lessons to
learn here (and a very interesting one it would be!) that in a
democracy it is very hard to adopt proposals that make life harder for
everyone? 

What would you think about making the VTs a more scarce currency, like
for example (rough sketch, not even protoproposal level, just to give
you the idea):

Limit the overall number of VTs to five times the number of players
(ouch - but that's the point!). If the bank is required to give out
VTs it doesn't have (by Rule 1684 or whatever else) it collects a tax
from all players, either a flat tax (everyone pays 1 Nth of the
required amount, where N is the number of active players) or a
percentage of the VTs in eir treasury. 

This would make spending VTs harder, non-voting penalties harsher etc
- you must admit that even after a balance restore transfers of 0.5 VTs
don't really make a difference if you have 20 of them to vote on five
proposals a week.

But it would not create more red tape, manual work etc, at least not
as much as the bookkeeping for plots, production etc. 


III. Foreign policy and Diplomacy

One of the things I enjoyed reading were the discussions about
internomic relations, wars, diplomacy, high treason etc, because these
are new areas of "game space". At the same time many socail and
political phenomena come up here: moral, ethics and politics; loyalty,
patriotism etc; communication and conflict solving between different
groups with different custums and cultures... This sounds like fun!

I was a bit surprized, though, how seriously some of you seemed to
take all these things - both Morendil and his critics (see below). I
would like to point out that, viweing the whole thing as "just" a
game, all the contributions and actions were highly interesting and
also connected with similar things in the real world - including
conflicts between patriotism and pacifism, differing opinions about
the "proper" means (and goals) for resolving conflicts, etc.

In my opinion Morendils actions not only triggered a series of highly
stimulating discussions, as well as new developments in the field of
diplomacy (including all the subsequent Internomic proposals). The
existence of "dissenters", "pacifists" or even "traitors" is also an
integral part of the politics of conflict - let's play that out and
enjoy it!


IV. Playing style

Which leads me to the mst difficult question I faced for my own style
of playing Agora, especially in respect to the "war" issue. Extreme
approaches to this would be either to behave just as I would in the
real world (where I am a Christian trying to ive according to the ten
commandments, and where I am trying hard to be honest and open,
because I don't like talking behind others' backs etc. pp.), or on the
other hand a kind of "it's just a game, innit?", roleplaying approach
- in games I can enjoy backstabbing former partners, using lies and
deception, and even play out killing others as long as that lies
within the rules of the game (yes, I like Cosims, ASL anyone?). That's
because in games I'm not dealing with real people but with cardboard
counters, or at least with other gamers who voluntarily agreed to play
the same game I play, according to the same rules (which may or may
not allow lying, killing and other acts that are immoral in the real
world) - nobody really dies or gets hurt, and the worst thing that can
happen is losing a game.

I think in Agora I'll have to choose a middle way - I'll try to be
myself as far as manners and procedures are concerned, but I will
behave just as if I was playing any other _game_ face to face, so
things that are allowed within the rules, including warfare (and
treason!) are ok as long as they contribute to the general enjoyment
of the game and don't completely spoil the game for others.


Well, I'll leave it at that for a start ... I guess you won't be
seeing another post this long from me anytime soon - I'll be glad if I
can just keep up with the everyday "duties" of playing along without
collecting too many blots and the like. Please let me know what you
think about these things, especially about the economics thing - if
some of you think it's feasible I'd like to try and turn the ideas
about scarce VTs into a proposal some time.

Thanks for reading and for all the friendly "Welcome"-mails!

Kolja A. (Klaus Herrmanns)


Disclaimer: I apologize for any style problems (Spi.. Whatsisname, a
yes, Spivak, I think, pronouns, which are new to me; repeating
arguments you have already had ad nauseam, etc) - if you noticed any
please let me know so I can do better next time. Thanks!


