No, I have never faced a really *tough* decision about using VTs or P-notes
based on available supply (even before my VT windfall).  I *have* faced
interesting decisions about whether or not to vote on a proposal for tactical
reasons, which is one of the things that keeps the game fun even without a
complex economy.  And yes, I think in a true democracy such as Agora, it *is*
very hard to adopt proposals that make life harder for everyone.  It's even
hard to adopt proposals that make life (significantly) harder for one Player,
such as an Officer.

>What would you think about making the VTs a more scarce currency, like
>for example (rough sketch, not even protoproposal level, just to give
>you the idea):

>Limit the overall number of VTs to five times the number of players
>(ouch - but that's the point!). If the bank is required to give out
>VTs it doesn't have (by Rule 1684 or whatever else) it collects a tax
>from all players, either a flat tax (everyone pays 1 Nth of the
>required amount, where N is the number of active players) or a
>percentage of the VTs in eir treasury. 

I'm not against making VTs really scarce, per se.  However, I think most of us
tend to be very wary of the possibility that it might become impossible for a
Player to vote at all (or make proposals, although some Players are content to
play without proposing).  The discussions generate a great deal (if not most)
of the fun here, of course, but voting and making proposals are the two
fundamental moves of the game - running the risk of preventing Players from
making these moves for extended periods of time is probably *not* a Good Thing.

>I was a bit surprized, though, how seriously some of you seemed to
>take all these things - both Morendil and his critics (see below). I
>would like to point out that, viweing the whole thing as "just" a
>game, all the contributions and actions were highly interesting and
