Ross Morgan-Linial wrote:

>On Thu, 3 Jul 1997, Klaus Herrmanns NB6_25 (3751) wrote:
>
>// In Germany income tax works like that: not only the gross amount of
>// tax you pay depends on your gross income, but the _percentage_ of your
>// gross income that is your tax varies with income, as well: from zero -
>// no income tax at all - for people with very low income (like me :) to
>// a top tax rate of 50% or so.
>
>Strangely enough, that's also (roughly) how the income tax works in the
>US.

I believe the US uses something like

  tax = P1% of your income below $L1
      + P2% of your income between $L1 and $L2
      + P3% of your income between $L2 and $L3, etc.

IOW, say P1=10, P2=20, P3=10, L1=10000, L2=20000, L3=30000:
  income $7000 -> tax $700
  income $12000 -> tax $1000 + $400 = $1400
  income $24000 -> tax $1000 + $2000 + $800 = $2800

